'''<U+00C9>rika Alejandra Olivera de la Fuente''' (born January 4, 1976 in [[Quinta Normal]]) is a female [[marathon (sports)|marathon]] [[Running|runner]] from [[Chile]]. She took the [[gold medal]] at the [[1999 Pan American Games]], setting a [[List of Pan American Games records in athletics|Pan American Games record]] at 2:37.41 hours. She won a bronze at the following edition in 2003. Starting in 1996, she represented her native country in three consecutive [[Summer Olympics]].

Olivera made her breakthrough at the junior level in 1994 when she won the [[10,000 metres]] gold and [[3000 metres]] [[bronze medal]]s at the [[South American Junior Championships in Athletics]]. The following year she upgraded to a gold and a [[silver medal]] at the [[Pan American Junior Championships]], before going on to complete a hat-trick of medals at the South American Junior Championships <U+2013> she secured a 10,000&nbsp;m and 3000&nbsp;m double and also won the [[1500 metres]] silver behind [[Bertha S<U+00E1>nchez]].<Ref>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/sajw.htm South American Junior Championships (Women)]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2010-10-30.</ref><ref>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/paj.htm Pan American Junior Championships]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2010-10-30.</ref>

Olivera is a two-time winner of the [[South American Cross Country Championships]], having beaten all comers in both the long and short races in 1999.<ref name=GBR>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/cxc.htm Continental Cross Country Championships and Cups]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2010-03-02.</ref> She is a five-time winner and course record holder of the [[Santiago Marathon]].<ref>: Juraj Gasparovic & Klaas Loonstra (2010-04-13). [http://www.arrs.net/HP_SantMa.htm Santiago Marathon]. [[Association of Road Racing Statisticians]]. Retrieved on 2010-10-30.</ref> She won the 1995 edition of the [[Buenos Aires Marathon]] in Argentina and placed fourth at the [[74th Saint Silvester Marathon]] in 1998.

She enjoyed success on the [[track and field|track]] at continental level, completing a [[10,000 metres]]/[[5000 metres]] silver medal double at both the [[1997 South American Championships in Athletics]] and [[2003 South American Championships in Athletics]]. Further to this, she won a silver and a bronze at the [[1999 South American Championships in Athletics|1999 edition]] of the competition.<ref>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/sacw.htm South American Championships (Women)]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2010-10-30.</ref> At the [[Ibero-American Championships]], she has won medals in a number of events, beginning with a 5000&nbsp;m gold medal and 10,000&nbsp;m bronze in [[1996 Ibero-American Championships|1996]], the 10,000&nbsp;m gold at the [[2000 Ibero-American Championships|2000 edition]], and finally a silver medal in the [[3000 metres steeplechase]] in [[2002 Ibero-American Championships|2002]].<ref>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/iac.htm Ibero American Championships]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2010-10-30.</ref>

Her personal best for the marathon is 2:32:23, set at the 1999 [[Rotterdam Marathon]], which is also the [[Chilean records in athletics|Chilean record]] for the event. She is also the national record holder over the [[half marathon]], 10,000&nbsp;m and 5000&nbsp;m.<ref>[http://www.fedachi.cl/web/estadisticas/records09/DAMASADULTAS.pdf Chilean Athletics Records - Women Outdoor]. Fedachi. Retrieved on 2010-10-30.</ref>

